	volume = {34},
	issn = {0256-5250},
	abstract = {The "Third industrial revolutions' - i.e. the rapid development of communication and information science and technologies and the progress in biology and genetics as well as their applications - has brought about radical changes in modern labour societies. The article focuses on the 1970s and 1980s: these two decades were a time of crisis in which European labour societies had to adapt their social and economic structures to the technological and scientific challenges. From the middle of the 1970s onwards, the Western European welfare states also showed signs of structural weakness which were countered by reforms. At about the same time, Eastern European socialist command economies suffered from stagnation. The crisis of socialist social policy was synonymous with a crisis of the full employment principle and the corresponding general obligation to work. Last but not least it was the crisis of the extraordinarily far-reaching system of consumer price subsidies. The article investigates the genesis of these crisis and reform processes in a comparative perspective, using the Federal Republic Germany and France as case studies on the one hand, the German Democratic Republic and Poland on the other.},
