@article{taris_review_2006,
	title = {Review of '{Citation} analysis in research evaluation'},
	volume = {15},
	abstract = {In 1964 the Institute for Scientific Information (ISI) launched its journal impact factor (IF), a quantitative measure that looks at the frequency with which an article in a journal is cited in a particular period (typically the current and the previous calendar year). The basic idea underlying the IF is that articles that are generally considered important for some reason are cited more frequently than other articles. Researchers should have a basic understanding of what an IF is, what it measures, what its strengths and limitations are, and how they can be used in a sensible way to evaluate the quality of research and researchers. Henk Moed's Citation Analysis in Research Evaluation provides a general introduction to these issues. Most importantly, it presents the definition of the IF-a ratio with the number of citations as the numerator, and the number of citable documents as the denominator. The book covers eight themes: assessment of research departments and journals in basic science; construction of the ISI citation indexes; assessment of research performance in the social sciences and humanities; accuracy of the ISI databases; what references and citations actually represent; the relationship between peer review and citation analysis; macro-level issues; and new developments in the field of bibliometrics. The book is written for members of the scholarly research community as a whole (i.e., not just psychologists) as well as those involved in research evaluation and research policy, including research policy makers, members of peer review committees, and those who will be subjected to an assessment of their research performance. Its aim is to provide these readers with a basic insight into the nature of citation analysis, the construction and calculation of its indicators, and their potentialities and limitations, especially with regard to their use in research evaluation. Although stylistically not a masterpiece, Citation Analysis in Research Evaluation is a valuable book for those interested in research evaluation. Its take-home message is that citation analysis is an interesting additional tool for evaluating research, but also that citation counts do not provide a complete, valid, reliable, and unbiased indication of the quality of journals, departments, or researchers within departments. This applies in general, but even stronger in fields that are not well covered by the ISI databases. While one may lament the disappearance of the traditional work and organizational (W/O) psychologist (being half practitioner, half researcher), the trend towards using IF is inevitable and perhaps even part of what may be called the maturation process of W/O psychology. Of course, this is not to say that citation analysis and impact factors should be the sole indicators of research excellence, and Henk Moed's book on this and related issues certainly helps in qualifying the value of these concepts, showing what is currently possible in bibliometrics and what is not. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2010 APA, all rights reserved)},
