ng else.' It is noted that publications serve many other purposes, eg, accounting for the time \& money spent in res, etc. Compensations are being made in the form of res carried out in collective projects in large instit's, where publication need not be used for justification. Major journals appear above the army of the journals for a particular discipline. Problems of the `noise' or extraneous information in citation indexing are considered, \& methods are presented for eliminating it, such as increasing the size of the samples on which the reckoning is based. It is felt that this field, with its self-organizing ramifications, deserves close study due to its possible profound effects on the future of sci'fic COMM. A. Heinrich.},
